[2] Venezuela (Zulia and national)
Date: Tue 25 Dec 2005
Source: Panorama, Venezuela [in Spanish trans. & summ. Mod. TY, edited]
<http://www.panodi.com/panodi/386422.html>

The number of people in Zulia ill [from dengue virus infection]
increased from 8181 in 2006 to 18 405 so far in 2007. Preventive
action is urged. The mosquito [_Aedes aegypti_] is adapted to the
urban environment and does not distinguish among social classes.
In 2007, 77 269 cases of classical dengue fever and DHF were
registered, an increase of 94 percent, which classified the disease
as epidemic, according to information from the Ministry of People's
Power for Health [MPPH]. The dengue cases in Zulia represent 24
percent of the national total and dengue increased 125 percent in the
region [over 2006]. The World Health Organization considers that [the
current epidemic] is related to the El Nino phenomenon.
Of the total of 77 269 dengue cases registered nationally, 18 405 are
in Zulia [state], a number which reflects more than double the cases
with occurred in Zulia last year [2006] during the same period.
According to the data provided by the Directorate General of
Epidemiology, Zulia leads in the number of dengue cases in the
country in marked contrast to the following states: Miranda (5.584
cases), Guarico (4.938) y Anzoategui (4.419). All [these] have been
declared dengue epidemic states.
The simultaneous presence of distinct [dengue virus] serotypes in a
given region increase the risk of possible outbreaks of DHF, of which
Zulia also has the greatest number: 1346 cases [of DHF] of a national
total of 6145.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Like much of tropical Latin America this year, Venezuela appears to
be experiencing a serious dengue epidemic. It would be interesting to
be able to plot the distribution, and if possible movement, of the
various dengue virus types throughout the western hemisphere this
year. Molecular epidemiological analysis could provide a powerful
tool to track that movement, the accompanying changes in the viruses
over time and changes in virulence associated with those changes.
A map of Venezuela showing the states mentioned can be accessed at:
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/venezuela.gif>. - Mod.TY]
