[4] Philippines (Cebu)
Date: Fri 21 Dec 2007
Source: News Balita Ph [edited]
<http://news.balita.ph/html/article.php?story=20071221202225239>

At least 48 deaths were attributed to mosquito-borne dengue fever in
this city this year [2007], with 101 more residents falling ill
because of the virus, health officials said.
As of 18 Dec [2007] the City Health Department recorded a total of 48
deaths in Cebu City.
There were 1946 cases recorded from 1 Jan - 18 Dec [2007]. Despite
the continuous increase in the number of cases, the Cebu City Dengue
Task Force decided not to heed the mayor's suggestion of pouring used
oil into a suspected breeding site of dengue-carrying mosquitoes in
Barangay Labangon [a barangay is a defined neighborhood. - Mod.TY].
Instead of using used oil, the City Health Department and the task
force will use chlorine or larvacide, whichever is more effective and
economical and safer to use. Assistant City Epidemiologist Durinda
Macasoncol said the task force advised against the use of used oil
after sanitary inspectors visited the lagoon in Labangon.
The lagoon, measuring some 1.4 hectares [3.46 acres], is suspected to
be the major breeding site of mosquitoes in Labangon, which has the
highest number of dengue cases among all 80 barangays.
"We were supposed to pour used oil in the lagoon but it did not push
through because we learned it could be harmful to the ecosystem.
We're still studying what is the more effective and economical way of
doing it, either we use chlorine or larvicide," Macasocol said.
The lagoon, which was originally a deep excavation for a building the
Gaisanos planned to build, will also have to be drained, she said.
But Cebu City Mayor Tomas Osmena was irked upon knowing the task
force did not heed his order to pour used oil on the pond and
threatened to fire personnel in charge of the campaign against dengue
fever. "My God, we already lost 50 lives and they're talking about
saving the earth," Osmena said.
Although pouring used oil in the lagoon will kill the mosquitoes,
Masacol said they opted not to push through with the mayor's
suggestion because it will only be good for one to 2 days. "Whatever
we put there, it will only be good for a couple of days because the
water continuously flows out of the lagoon. We are studying this so
we can come up with something that has long-term benefits," Macasocol added.
--
Communicated by:
ProMED Rapporteur Brent Barrett
[This is an example of inappropriate action being proposed by a
political leader based on incomplete or inaccurate information. While
the lagoon may indeed be a breeding ground for mosquitoes, it is
highly unlikely that the dengue virus vector mosquito, _Aedes
aegypti_, is breeding there. _Ae. aegypti_ requires fresh water
catchments, usually in and immediately around houses and other
buildings. Efforts at control of dengue virus transmission should be
aimed at these _Aedes aegypti_ breeding sites. This report
illustrates the need for scientists to work closely with policy
decision makers, and for both to engage the public in elimination of
these mosquito vector breeding sites in their houses and other buildings.
A map of the Philippine provinces showing Cebu Province can be
accessed at: <http://www.chanrobles.com/philippinemapofprovinces.htm>
and an interactive ProMED health map showing the location of Cebu
City within the province can be accessed at:
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=11.7,122.9,5>. - Mod.TY]
